<p>Desbuquois dysplasia (DBQD) is an autosomal recessive chondrodysplasia belonging to the multiple dislocation group and characterized by severe prenatal and postnatal growth retardation (less than -5 SD), joint laxity, short extremities, and progressive scoliosis. The main radiologic features are short long bones with metaphyseal splay, a 'Swedish key' appearance of the proximal femur (exaggerated trochanter), and advance carpal and tarsal bone age with a delta phalanx (summary by Huber et al., 2009).</p>

<p>[Huber, C., Oules, B., Bertoli, M., Chami, M., Fradin, M., Alanay, Y., Al-Gazali, L. I., Ausems, M. G. E. M., Bitoun, P., Cavalcanti, D. P., Krebs, A., Le Merrer, M., {and 9 others} Identification of CANT1 mutations in Desbuquois dysplasia. Am. J. Hum. Genet. 85: 706-710, 2009.]<br/></p>